@startuml ca-rekey-window
' The CA re-key runbook, its finite dual-trust window, and the deferred bidirectional failure it can leave behind.
' Source of truth: docs/src/security/tls.md
!include _style.puml

skinparam wrapWidth 340

actor "Platform\nengineer" as PE #FFE4B5
participant "cert-manager" as CM #F5F5F5
participant "trust-manager\n**Bundle** kaalm-ca" as TM #F5F5F5
participant "projected **ConfigMap**\nkaalm-ca\n/var/run/kaalm/ca.crt" as CFG #FFD580
participant "**Agent** process" as AG #E6E6FA
participant "**Gateway**" as GW #90EE90

note over AG
  Holds **two** pools, both built
  from the same CA bundle:
  **ClientCAs** verifies callers (inbound)
  **RootCAs** verifies peers it dials (outbound)
end note

note over PE, GW #FFF8DC
  Routine **renewal** is not this. kaalm-ca pins
  privateKey.rotationPolicy: Never, so renewal re-uses the CA
  key pair, every existing leaf keeps verifying, and no window
  is needed. Only a **re-key** (compromise recovery) runs the
  steps below, and it is a manual runbook: no operator code
  implements either path.
end note

group dual-trust window: both the old and the new CA are trusted (finite)

  == Runbook step 1: add the new CA as a second Bundle source ==
  PE -> TM : add new CA alongside the old\nsources: [old CA, new CA]
  hnote over TM #FFD580 : window **OPENS**
  TM -> CFG : re-project bundle = old CA + new CA
  CFG -> AG : kubelet swaps the ..data symlink
  AG -> AG : rebuild **both** pools\n(ClientCAs and RootCAs)
  CFG -> GW : kubelet swaps the ..data symlink
  GW -> GW : rebuild **both** pools

  == Runbook step 2: force leaf re-issuance ==
  PE -> CM : cmctl renew on the leaf Certificates
  CM -> GW : kaalm-gateway-tls re-issued\nunder the **new** CA key
  CM -> AG : {name}-tls re-issued\nunder the **new** CA key
  note over AG, GW #FFF8DC
    This is where a missed reload turns fatal, not step 1.
    The failure is **deferred**: an agent that never reloaded
    sailed through step 1, because the old leaves still
    chained to the old CA it still trusted.
  end note

  == Runbook step 3: remove the old source ==
  PE -> TM : remove old CA source, once no\nlive leaf chains to it
  hnote over TM #FFD580 : window **CLOSES**
  TM -> CFG : re-project bundle = new CA only
end

alt the agent rebuilt both pools inside the window
  AG -> GW : LLM request: RootCAs verifies\nthe re-issued gateway leaf
  GW -> AG : POST /v1/message: agent's re-issued\nleaf accepted by ClientCAs
else the agent missed the CA-bundle change
  AG -[#B71C1C]->x GW : **outbound** fails: RootCAs still holds only\nthe old CA, so the new gateway leaf\nfails verification
  GW -[#B71C1C]->x AG : **inbound** fails: ClientCAs still holds only\nthe old CA, so the gateway's re-issued\nclient cert is rejected
  note over AG, GW #FFF8DC
    Broken in **both** directions at once. Rebuilding one pool
    and not the other gives this same symptom in one direction
    only. The window is finite, so the agent does not recover
    on its own.
  end note
end

legend bottom
  Starter templates watch $KAALM_CA_CERT and rebuild both pools on change, which makes this
  transparent. Custom images carry the same obligation: the inbound server rebuilds ClientCAs via a
  tls.Config.GetConfigForClient callback returning a config with the fresh pool, and the outbound
  HTTP client rebuilds RootCAs. A CA-bundle change MUST rebuild both.
endlegend
@enduml
